{{use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Starbox begin | name = [[Henry Draper catalogue|HD]] 164595 }}{{Starbox image | image = [[File:Hercules constellation HD 164595.png|250px]] | caption = Position of star HD 164595 in the constellation [[Hercules (constellation)|Hercules]] }}{{Starbox observe | epoch=J2000 | ra={{RA|18|00|38.894}}<ref name="SIMBAD"/> | dec={{DEC|+29|34|18.92}}<ref name="SIMBAD"/> | constell=[[Hercules (constellation)|Hercules]] | appmag_v=7.08<ref>{{cite journal|bibcode=1972RGOB..176..127E|title=UBV photoelectric observations: I. Stars within 25 parsec of the sun; II. Stars in quasar and galaxy fields; III. Stars in Kapteyn Selected Areas; IV. Miscellaneous stars|journal=Royal Observatory Bulletin|volume=176|pages=127|last=Epps|first=E. A.|year=1972}}</ref> }} {{Starbox character | class = G2V D<ref name="SIMBAD"/> | b-v = }} <!--{{Starbox astrometry | prop_mo_ra = | prop_mo_dec = | parallax = | p_error = | parallax_footnote = | absmag_v = }}--> {{Starbox detail | mass = 0.99<ref name="arxiv"/> | radius = | gravity = 4.44 ± 0.05<ref name="arxiv"/> | temperature = 5790 ± 40<ref name="arxiv"/> | metal_fe = −0.06<ref name="arxiv"/> | age_gyr = 4.5<ref name="arxiv"/> }}{{Starbox catalog | names = [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;164595, [[Hipparcos Catalogue|HIP]]&nbsp;88194, SAO 85632, BD+29 3165. }}{{Starbox reference | Simbad = HD+164595 | EPE = | ARICNS = }} {{Starbox end}}
'''HD&nbsp;164595'''<ref name="SIMBAD"/> is a [[G-type star|G-type]] [[star]] located in the [[constellation]] of [[Hercules (constellation)|Hercules]], {{convert|28.927|pc|ly|abbr=off|lk=on}} from Earth that is [[Solar analog|notably similar to the Sun]].<ref name="arxiv"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://server7.sky-map.org/starview?object_type=1&object_id=480070&object_name=HIP%2088194&locale=NL|title=HD 164595 - Star - SKY-MAP|publisher=}}</ref> With an [[apparent magnitude]] of 7.075,<ref name="SIMBAD"/> the star can be found with binoculars or a small telescope in the constellation [[Hercules (constellation)|Hercules]].
HD&nbsp;164595 has one known planet, {{nowrap|[[HD 164595 b]]}}, which orbits HD&nbsp;164595 every 40&nbsp;days.<ref name=NasaExoplanetArchive>{{cite web | url=http://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/DisplayOverview/nph-DisplayOverview?objname=HD+164595+b&type=CONFIRMED_PLANET | title=HD 164595 b Confirmed Planet Overview Page | work=[[NASA]] | accessdate=31 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Courcol|first=B.|last2=Bouchy|first2=F.|last3=Pepe|first3=F.|last4=Santerne|first4=A.|last5=Delfosse|first5=X.|last6=Arnold|first6=L.|last7=Astudillo-Defru|first7=N.|last8=Boisse|first8=I.|last9=Bonfils|first9=X.|date=2015-09-01|title=The SOPHIE search for northern extrasolar planets|url=http://www.aanda.org/10.1051/0004-6361/201526329|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|language=en|volume=581|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201526329|issn=0004-6361|arxiv=1506.07144|bibcode=2015A&A...581A..38C}}</ref> It was detected with the [[Doppler spectroscopy|radial velocity]] technique with the [[SOPHIE échelle spectrograph|SOPHIE echelle spectrograph]]. The planet has a minimal mass equivalent of 16 [[Earth mass|Earths]].<ref name=NasaExoplanetArchive />
The star has the same [[stellar classification]] as the Sun: G2V. It has a similar temperature, at {{val|5,790|ul=K}} compared with {{val|5,778|u=K}} for the Sun. It has a lower logarithm of [[metallicity]] ratio, at −0.06 compared with 0.00, and a slightly younger age, at 4.5 versus 4.6&nbsp;[[Gigayear|billion years]].<ref name=aaa563_A52/><ref name=nssdc>{{cite web |last=Williams |first=D. R. |url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/sunfact.html |title=Sun Fact Sheet |publisher=[[NASA]] |year=2004 |accessdate=23 June 2009 }}</ref>{{efn|An exact solar twin would be a G2V star with a {{val|5,778|u=K}} temperature, be 4.6 billion years old, with the correct metallicity and a 0.1% [[solar luminosity]] variation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2013/08jan_sunclimate/|title=Solar Variability and Terrestrial Climate - NASA Science|publisher=|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref><ref name="nssdc"/> }}
In 2016, HD&nbsp;164595 briefly attracted media attention after it was reported that a possible [[SETI]] signal had been detected from the direction of the star in the previous year. The signal was only heard once and never confirmed by other telescopes, and is thought to have been due to terrestrial interference.
== Signal observation and SETI == [[File:Perfil de la señal de radio de HD 164595.jpg|thumb|left|Plot of radio signal intensity]] On 15 May 2015, a brief, single radio signal at 11&nbsp;GHz (2.7&nbsp;cm wavelength)<ref name="ArsTechnica">{{cite web |last1=Berger |first1=Eric |title=Ars Technica |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2016/08/seti-has-observed-a-strong-signal-that-may-originate-from-a-sun-like-star/|website=Ars Technica |publisher=Ars Technica |accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> was observed in the direction of HD&nbsp;164595 by a team led by N.&nbsp;N. Bursov<ref name="CD-20160827">{{cite web |url=http://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=36248 |title=An Interesting SETI Candidate in Hercules |publisher=Centauri Dreams |date=27 August 2016 |accessdate=29 August 2016 |last=Gilster |first=Paul}}</ref> involving [[Claudio Maccone]] at the [[RATAN-600]] radio observatory. The signal may be due to terrestrial radio-frequency interference or [[gravitational lens]]ing from a more distant source.<ref>{{cite journal|title=SETI observations on the RATAN-600 telescope in 2015 and detection of a strong signal in the direction of HD 164595 |last1=Bursov |first1=N. |last2=Filippova |first2=L. |last3=Filippov |first3=V. |last4=Gindilis |first4=L. |last5=Maccone |first5=C. |displayauthors=etal |date=2016 |journal=IAA SETI Permanent Committee |location=Guadalajara, Mexico}}</ref><ref name="renamed_from_20160829_on_20160901024247">{{cite web |title=Mystery radio signal may be from distant star system — or a military transmitter |url=http://www.kurzweilai.net/mystery-radio-signal-may-be-from-distant-star-system-or-a-military-transmitter |date=29 August 2016 |work=[[KurzweilAI]] |accessdate=31 August 2016 }}</ref> It was observed only once (for two seconds), by a single team, at a single telescope, giving it a [[Post-detection policy#Significance of transmission|Rio Scale]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Rio scale calculator |url=http://avsport.org/IAA/riocalc.htm}}</ref> score of 1 (insignificant) or 2 (low). Discussions in the media from 29 August 2016 onwards featured speculation that the signal could be caused by an [[isotropic beacon]] from a [[Kardashev scale#Definition|Type II civilization]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Seemangal |first1=Robin |title=Not a Drill: SETI Is Investigating a Possible Extraterrestrial Signal From Deep Space |url=http://observer.com/2016/08/not-a-drill-seti-is-investigating-a-possible-extraterrestrial-signal-from-deep-space/ |accessdate=29 August 2016 |date=29 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zolfagharifard |first1=Ellie |title=Is Earth being contacted by ALIENS? Mystery radio signals coming from a Sun-like star baffle scientists |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3763416/Is-Earth-contacted-ALIENS-Mystery-radio-signals-coming-sun-like-star-baffle-scientists.html |accessdate=29 August 2016 |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>
The senior astronomer of the [[SETI Institute]], [[Seth Shostak]], stated that confirmation by another telescope is required.<ref name="GeekWire"/> Astronomer [[Nicholas Suntzeff]] of [[Texas A&M University]] stated that the signal is in a military frequency band, and that it could have been a satellite downlink, implying that some such systems may be kept secret and therefore would be unknown to SETI scientists.<ref name="ArsTechnica"/>
SETI and [[Active SETI|METI]] studies followed with the [[Allen Telescope Array]] and the Boquete Optical SETI Observatory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/local/article/Leaked-space-signal-report-has-SETI-groups-9191169.php|title='Leaked' space signal report has SETI groups scrambling|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="GeekWire">{{cite web|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/signal-seti-interest-hd164595/|title=They're not saying it's aliens, but signal traced to sunlike star sparks SETI interest|date=29 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Also, scientists at Berkeley SETI Research Center at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] observed HD&nbsp;164595 using the [[Green Bank Telescope]] as part of the [[Breakthrough Listen]] program. No signal was detected at the position and frequency of the transient reported by the RATAN group.<ref>{{cite web |title=Preliminary analysis of star HD 164595 |url=http://seti.berkeley.edu/HD164595_summary.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Breakthrough Listen Follow-up of a Transient Signal from the RATAN-600 Telescope in the Direction of HD 164595 |url=http://seti.berkeley.edu/HD164595.pdf}}</ref>
The [[Special Astrophysical Observatory]] of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]] has since released an official statement that the signal is of a "most probable terrestrial origin".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.sao.ru/Doc-en/SciNews/2016/Sotnikova/| title=SETI| publisher=}}</ref>
