{{Speciesbox | image =Melanobatrachus indicus.jpg | status = EN | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite journal | author = Biju, S.D. | author2 = Vasudevan, Karthikeyan | author3 = Bhuddhe, Gajanan Dasaramji | author4 = Dutta, Sushil | author5 = Srinivasulu, Chelmala | author6 = Vijayakumar, S.P. | title = ''Melanobatrachus indicus'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2004 | page = e.T13032A3406563 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2004 | url = http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/13032/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2004.RLTS.T13032A3406563.en | access-date = 3 January 2018}}</ref> | taxon = Melanobatrachus indicus | authority = [[Richard Henry Beddome|Beddome]], 1878 | parent_authority = [[Richard Henry Beddome|Beddome]], 1878 }} '''''Melanobatrachus''''' is a genus of [[Microhylidae|narrow-mouthed frog]]s (family Microhylidae) that contains a single species, '''''Melanobatrachus indicus'''''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/herpetology/amphibia/Amphibia/Anura/Microhylidae/Melanobatrachinae/Melanobatrachus |title=''Melanobatrachus'' Beddome, 1878 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2015 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.0 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> It is known under a number of common names, including '''Kerala Hills frog''', '''black microhylid frog''', and '''Malabar black narrow-mouthed frog'''. It is [[endemic]] to wet evergreen forests of southern [[Western Ghats]] in [[Kerala]] and [[Tamil Nadu]] states of [[India]].<ref name=frost>{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/herpetology/amphibia/Amphibia/Anura/Microhylidae/Melanobatrachinae/Melanobatrachus/Melanobatrachus-indicus |title=''Melanobatrachus indicus'' Beddome, 1878 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2015 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.0 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>
''Melanobatrachus indicus'' is a rare species<ref name=IUCN/> that was only rediscovered in 1997.<ref name=EDGE>{{cite web |url=http://www.edgeofexistence.org/amphibians/species_info.php?id=602 |title=Black Microhylid Frog (''Melanobatrachus indicus'') |author= |year= |work=Evolutionarily Distinct and Globally Endangered (EDGE) species |publisher=The Zoological Society of London |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref> It lives amongst leaf-litter, rocks and other ground cover of moist evergreen tropical forests.<ref name=IUCN/>
''Melanobatrachus indicus'' is an [[Evolutionarily Distinct and Globally Endangered]] (EDGE) species.<ref name=EDGE/> It is the sole species in [[subfamily]] [[Melanobatrachinae]], and it is classified as "[[Endangered species|Endangered]]" by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref name=IUCN/>
