'''Thomas Godfrey''' (December 1704 – December 1749) was an optician and inventor in the [[Thirteen Colonies|American colonies]], who around 1730 invented the [[octant (instrument)|octant]]. At approximately the same time an Englishman, [[John Hadley]], also invented the octant independently.
Godfrey was born on his family's farm in Bristol Township, near [[Germantown, Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].
[[Benjamin Franklin]] describes Godfrey at length in his ''[[The Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin|Autobiography]]'', referring to him as a "Great Mathematician" who nevertheless was "not a pleasing Companion", demanding in conversations a "universal Precision in every thing said."<ref name="franklin">{{cite book | last = Franklin | first = Benjamin | authorlink = Benjamin Franklin | title = The Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin | publisher = [[Dover]] | location = Mineola | date = 1996 | isbn = 978-0-486-29073-7 }}</ref>
Godfrey's son, also [[Thomas Godfrey (poet)|Thomas Godfrey]], died at only 26, but had already published several popular works, including [[The Prince of Parthia]], a play that remains well known to this day.
