In biology, the '''wonderful life theory''', also known as '''contingency theory''', postulates that after hundreds of different [[phylum|phyla]] evolved during the [[Cambrian|Cambrian period]], many of them subsequently became extinct, leaving the relatively few phyla that exist today.<ref>{{cite book| title=Dictionary of Theories| year=2002| page=557| last=Bothamley| first=Jennifer| publisher=Barnes and Noble}}</ref>  The theory was first suggested in 1989 by [[Stephen Jay Gould]] in his book ''[[Wonderful Life (book)|Wonderful Life]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine| title=Whose View of Life| last=Lewin| first=Roger| date=1992-05-01| magazine=Discover Magazine| url=http://discovermagazine.com/1992/may/whoseviewoflife52}}</ref>

